                                 INTERLEAVING                                 ____________

            Definition - Interleave is the process of  configuring  the  memory
       addressing  so  that  consecutive  addresses  are not stored in the SAME
       memory module.  This allows increasing memory speed by overlapping  part
       of the operation of different memory modules.  What is important for the
       Operator to realize is that when interleave is on,  the  memory  can  be
       accessed at a greater rate of speed.

            We are concerned  with  interleave  because,  once  any  memory  is
       deselected,  the  interleave  must  be TURNED OFF.  This is important to
       remember, for if memory is left in "4-WAY" interleave, the  system  will
       not come up.

            To turn the interleave OFF, simply turn the knob labeled INTERLEAVE
       to  the  OFF  position  on  the  TRM10LX.  If memory has been deselected
       before you did your deselection, interleave will be in the OFF  position
       already.

            To turn the  interleave  OFF  on  the  ARM10LS,  first  locate  the
       INTERLEAVE  section  to  the right of the two SECTOR INDEX (MSB and LSB)
       switches.  Toggle this switch from 4-WAY to 1-WAY.  If memory  has  been
       deselected  before  your  deselection,  this switch will be in the 1-WAY
       position.




















